A mentally ill weightlifting blogger made this point, but back in the day people had an insane activity level. Even if you had a sedentary desk job or were like a doctor, you still had to walk down to the butcher store, carry groceries through town, hammer nails around the house.

We've all had those days when we hauled a heavy refrigerator up ten flights of stairs, went to the gym, went on a long walk in the woods with a friend, played bowling, etc. Just multiple physical fun stimulating activities. The more you do, the more your work capacity increases.

The Harold Hillman thesis:

1. Most biochemical research techniques have 24+ unproven assumptions.

2. Most cell structures except the nucleus/mitochondria are electronic microscope image artefacts.

3. There are no synapses, the chemical transmitter hypothesis is probably fake.

Basically the brain and spinal cord on the cellular level consists of nerve cells (which are plainly visible with simple methods and excitable), the rest is naked nuclei in a granular substance that gets "interpreted" as various cells using electronic microscoping meme methods.

The way that the Bible describes Leviathan as "lurking" behind the scenes, through the entirety of history, "influencing" current events, Empires, culture, etc. reminds me of Gene Wolfe's Megatherians controlling the world secretly through influencing people to do things, agents.

The Bible says God put Leviathan in the water, which I think can be taken in the Paracelsian sense of "the water element", as the undines who live there. But Lovecraft too has this image of twisting monstrous creatures deep in the sea influencing events, people from the darkness.
It's obvious that both these are conscious depictions of Leviathan under different names, but art makes it easier to visualize some concepts like this

A friend of mine was very correct that in the early Internet there was finally a snap away from "celebrity culture" and it was seen as distasteful to even mention the names of celebrities, but at one point in the 10s/20s, this reversed, and people went back to their idle chatter.

I guess part of it is the somewhat decentralized nature of a fragmented internet gave way to more corporate control through "astroturfing", manipulating algorithms, viral marketing, so when people no longer felt shamed for it, they just resumed gossip, celebrity discussions, etc.
